## 🏛️ Clean API Architecture

As an API grows, disorganized code becomes unmaintainable. Clean architecture separates concerns into layers, making code testable, scalable, and easy to understand.

---

## 1️⃣ Why Architecture Matters

**Without architecture:**
```javascript
app.post('/users', async (req, res) => {
  // 100+ lines of validation, database operations,
  // email sending, error handling — all in one function
})
```

This leads to:
- Code that's impossible to test
- Repeated logic
- Bugs that cascade across features
- Difficulty onboarding new developers

---

## 2️⃣ The Three-Layer Architecture

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  HTTP Layer (Routes / Controllers)                   │
│  - Parse request, validate input                     │
│  - Call service layer                                │
│  - Format HTTP response                              │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Business Logic Layer (Services)                     │
│  - Core application logic                            │
│  - Orchestrates calls to multiple repositories       │
│  - Framework-agnostic                                │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Data Access Layer (Models / Repositories)           │
│  - Database queries                                  │
│  - Data transformation                               │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

---

## 3️⃣ Controllers — HTTP Layer

Controllers handle HTTP concerns ONLY:

```javascript
// controllers/userController.js
const UserService = require('../services/userService')

async function register(req, res, next) {
  try {
    const user = await UserService.register(req.body)  // Delegate to service
    res.status(201).json({ success: true, user })
  } catch (error) {
    next(error)  // Forward to error middleware
  }
}

async function getUser(req, res, next) {
  try {
    const user = await UserService.getUserById(req.params.id)
    res.json(user)
  } catch (error) {
    next(error)
  }
}

module.exports = { register, getUser }
```

---

## 4️⃣ Services — Business Logic Layer

Services contain the WHAT of your application:

```javascript
// services/userService.js
const User = require('../models/User')
const bcrypt = require('bcryptjs')
const { sendWelcomeEmail } = require('./emailService')
const AppError = require('../utils/AppError')

async function register({ name, email, password }) {
  // 1. Check for duplicates
  const existing = await User.findOne({ email: email.toLowerCase() })
  if (existing) throw new AppError('Email already registered', 409)

  // 2. Hash password
  const hashed = await bcrypt.hash(password, 12)

  // 3. Create user
  const user = await User.create({ name, email: email.toLowerCase(), password: hashed })

  // 4. Send welcome email (fire and forget)
  sendWelcomeEmail(user.email, user.name).catch(console.error)

  // 5. Return safe user object (no password)
  const { password: _, ...safeUser } = user.toObject()
  return safeUser
}

async function getUserById(id) {
  const user = await User.findById(id)
  if (!user) throw new AppError('User not found', 404)
  return user
}

module.exports = { register, getUserById }
```

---

## 5️⃣ Custom Error Classes

```javascript
// utils/AppError.js
class AppError extends Error {
  constructor(message, statusCode) {
    super(message)
    this.statusCode = statusCode
    this.isOperational = true  // Expected error (vs programming bug)
  }
}

module.exports = AppError

// Usage
throw new AppError('User not found', 404)
throw new AppError('Email already taken', 409)
throw new AppError('Token expired', 401)
```

---

## 6️⃣ Global Error Handler

```javascript
// middleware/errorHandler.js
function errorHandler(err, req, res, next) {
  // Set defaults
  err.statusCode = err.statusCode || 500
  err.message = err.message || 'Internal server error'

  // Mongoose: invalid ObjectId
  if (err.name === 'CastError') {
    err.statusCode = 404
    err.message = 'Resource not found'
  }

  // Mongoose: duplicate key
  if (err.code === 11000) {
    const field = Object.keys(err.keyValue)[0]
    err.statusCode = 409
    err.message = `${field} already exists`
  }

  // Mongoose: validation errors
  if (err.name === 'ValidationError') {
    err.statusCode = 400
    err.message = Object.values(err.errors).map(e => e.message).join(', ')
  }

  // JWT errors
  if (err.name === 'JsonWebTokenError') {
    err.statusCode = 401
    err.message = 'Invalid token'
  }

  if (err.name === 'TokenExpiredError') {
    err.statusCode = 401
    err.message = 'Token expired'
  }

  // Log stack trace in development
  if (process.env.NODE_ENV === 'development') {
    console.error(err.stack)
  }

  res.status(err.statusCode).json({
    error: err.message,
    ...(process.env.NODE_ENV === 'development' && { stack: err.stack })
  })
}

module.exports = errorHandler
```

---

## 7️⃣ Async Handler Wrapper

Avoid try/catch in every controller:

```javascript
// utils/asyncHandler.js
const asyncHandler = (fn) => (req, res, next) =>
  Promise.resolve(fn(req, res, next)).catch(next)

module.exports = asyncHandler

// Usage in routes
router.post('/register', asyncHandler(register))  // No try/catch needed
```

---

## 8️⃣ Input Validation as Middleware

```javascript
// middleware/validate.js
const { z } = require('zod')

function validate(schema) {
  return (req, res, next) => {
    const result = schema.safeParse(req.body)
    if (!result.success) {
      return res.status(422).json({
        error: 'Validation failed',
        details: result.error.flatten()
      })
    }
    req.body = result.data  // Use parsed/sanitized data
    next()
  }
}

// schemas.js
const registerSchema = z.object({
  name: z.string().min(2),
  email: z.string().email(),
  password: z.string().min(8)
})

// Usage
router.post('/register', validate(registerSchema), asyncHandler(register))
```

---

## 9️⃣ The Complete Route → Controller → Service Flow

```
POST /api/auth/register
       ↓
  Rate limiter middleware
       ↓
  validate(registerSchema) — zod validation
       ↓
  register controller — parse req, call service
       ↓
  userService.register() — business logic
       ↓
  User.create() — database
       ↓
  Response ← controller formats and sends
```

---

## 💡 Summary

| Layer | Responsibility | File |
|---|---|---|
| Routes | URL mapping | `routes/userRoutes.js` |
| Controllers | HTTP layer | `controllers/userController.js` |
| Services | Business logic | `services/userService.js` |
| Models | Database schema | `models/User.js` |
| Middleware | Reusable pipeline steps | `middleware/auth.js` |
| Utils | Shared helpers | `utils/AppError.js` |
| Error handler | Central error formatting | `middleware/errorHandler.js` |
